{
  "texts": [
    "This formulation ensures that important tokens dominate gradient updates.",
    "Conceptual OverviewThe combined insights from these related works form the basis for DRaFT-Q, which integrates dynamic rank allocation and reward-weighted learning into a single lightweight framework.",
    "Input DataQuantized LLM (frozen)LoRA Adapters (Dynamic Rank)Reward-Weighted Loss Overview of DRaFT-QDRaFT-Q (Dynamic Rank-Aware Fine-Tuning under Quantization) is a PEFT method that combines two adaptive innovations to optimize low-bit model finetuning: (1) dynamic LoRA rank allocation driven by real-time learning signals, and (2) reward-weighted token loss that biases optimization toward high-utility outputs.",
    "Unlike conventional LoRA and QLoRA, DRaFT-Q adapts the size of its adapters layer-wise based on short-term statistics like loss deltas or gradient norms.",
    "This lets DRaFT-Q allocate more capacity to struggling layers and shrink less active ones, all while staying within strict VRAM budgets."
  ]
